      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Those noises can be unsettling, and while sometimes they are just the settling of the structure, you should definitely investigate them, especially if they sound like scratching or tapping. In a new build, minor settling noises are somewhat normal, but persistent, distinct sounds often point to something else.\n\nThe most common culprits are often related to insulation shifting, plumbing expansion/contraction, or sometimes even pests, which is why you should check the areas where the wall cavities are accessible. If the sounds are rhythmic or localized, you might want to gently inspect the areas behind the drywall near the noise source, making sure nothing is loose or vibrating against the framing.\n\nIf you suspect pests, that's a different level of concern, so if you hear actual scurrying, you should definitely have a professional take a look. But for general settling, it's usually just the house adjusting to its new environment.\n\nIt's always better to check than to ignore it, especially since you're working in a confined space, which makes noises seem louder. Keep a careful log of when the sounds occur—is it when the HVAC kicks on, when the house temperature changes, or when it's completely still? That data can be very helpful for diagnosis.",
